Although there is variation in EOs benefit to poultry growth, the antioxidant activity of many EOs is well-known (
 Baratta et al., 1998; 
 Ruberto et al., 2000; 
 Martucci et al., 2015). Rosemary oil, thymol, carvacrol, oregano, ginger, and coriander all possess antioxidant activity (
 Wei and Shibamoto, 2007). An oxidation deterioration test involving the application of EOs to lard indicated that 0.20% oregano possessed the most antioxidant capacity followed by thyme, dittany, marjoram, spearmint, then lavender (
 Economou et al., 1991). 
 Economou et al. (1991) also found that combinations of thyme and marjoram and thyme and spearmint EOs also had potential synergistic properties in protecting lard from oxidation. These properties benefit bird health and can be marketable if EOs are used on the finished product (
 Lee et al., 2004b; 
 Diaz-Sanchez et al., 2015).
